[[Category:Etymologies of geographic names|Trakai, Names of]]

'''Neorxnawang''' (also '''Neorxenawang, Neorxnawong'''; possibly "field of contentment"<ref name=MCKINNEL51>McKinnell (2005:51).</ref>) is an [[Old English]] term used to translate the [[Christianity|Christian]] concept of "paradise" in [[Anglo-Saxon literature]].<ref name=SIMEK229>Simek (2007:229).</ref> The term is often theorized as originally having referred to a [[Germanic mythology|mythological]] "heavenly meadow", or place without toil or worries, in [[Germanic paganism]].<ref name=JEEP554>Jeep (2001:554).</ref>

==Etymology==
While the second half of the word, "-''wang''", is widely considered to mean "field" and ''waggs'' appears for "paradise" in [[Gothic language|Gothic]], the first half of the word has not resulted in a standard form, though at least a dozen attempts have been made to interpret it.<ref name=SIMEK229/> Scholar [[Rudolf Simek]] states that it is possible to consider the term as a [[Proto-Germanic]] term for "[[Asgard]]" or "Other World" due to the unclear meaning, that Christian authors who used it seemed to have a poor understanding of it as well, and that it corresponds with the [[North Germanic languages|North Germanic]] terms ''[[Iðavöllr]]'' (possibly "field of activity" or "the continually renewing, rejuvenating field") and ''[[Glæsisvellir]]'' ("the shining fields").<ref name=SIMEK229/>

19th century scholar [[Jacob Grimm]] comments that etymological connections have been proposed between ''[[Norns|Norn]]'' and ''Neorxnawang'', but says that the theory raises etymological and lore problems: "The A. gen. pl. neorxana, which only occurs in 'neorxena wong' = paradisus, has been proposed, but the abbreviation would be something unheard of, and even the nom. sing. neorxe or neorxu at variance with norn; besides,the [[Parcae]] are nowhere found connected with paradise."<ref name=GRIMM405>Grimm (1882:405).</ref>

Late 19th and early 20th century philologist [[James Bright]] proposes that the variant ''neorxena-'' element derives from the phrase ''ne wyrcan'', meaning "no working".<ref name="BRIGHT1913">Bright (1913:334).</ref>

In a 2012 paper, Joseph S. Hopkins and Haukur Þorgeirsson propose a connection between Old Norse ''[[Fólkvangr]]'', an afterlife location overseen by the goddess [[Freyja]], and a variety of other Germanic words referring to the afterlife that contain extensions of Proto-Germanic *''wangaz'' (including Old English ''Neorxnawang''), potentially pointing to an early Germanic '''*wangaz'' of the dead'.<ref name="HOPKINS-HAUKUR-14-17">Hopkins and Haukur (2012:14-17).</ref>

==See also==
* ''[[Muspilli]]'', an Old High German poem where pagan vocabulary and Christian concepts mingle
* [[Þrúðvangr]], the field of the god Thor
* [[Firmament|Welkin]], an Old English term for the sky, heavens, and clouds

